english:
  title: Postscript to the Newly Published Ritual of Sacrificial Offerings
  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In ancient times, when the ritual of sacrificial offerings was conducted at the National Academy, the ceremonies were exceedingly simple, and their detailed procedures have not been transmitted to us. Since the Tang Dynasty, there existed the Kaiyuan Rituals, and the Song Dynasty produced the Zhenghe New Rituals. Yet these too fell into disuse and were largely abandoned. Master Zhu Wenggong of the Purple Yang school often lamented this state of affairs, repeatedly requesting that the rituals be restored and revived. He harbored ambitions to correct and refine the order of ceremonies, but ultimately could not bring this to completion.

    The ritual text published by the Ningguo Prefectural Academy was compiled by the learned scholar Meng Zhizhen from an earlier generation. He gathered the Sacrificial Ritual of Zhu Wenggong, the Diagrams of Robes and Caps from the Lake School, and wove them into a single volume. The Essential Knowledge of Sacrificial Offerings and the Ritual of Cangzhou Vegetable Offering were also included in the appendix. The positions and orientations of the spiritual tablets, the specifications of vessels and ceremonial garments, and the procedures of ascending, descending, and presenting libations—all were comprehensively documented. Only the so-called Zhu Wenggong Ritual still retained the old ways of the Kaiyuan system, those aspects which Master Zhu had once wished to reform but never completed.

    In the year of Jianwen xingyun, the Surveillance Commissioner Xian Gong of Jeolla Province, lamenting how the sacrificial rites in the districts and counties had fallen into disorder, reported this matter to the state and obtained the ritual texts from the National Confucian Academy. Intending to have them carved into wooden blocks for printing, he entrusted the matter to the Prefect Liu Gong. Liu Gong also gladly took up the task. Not long after, Surveillance Commissioner Zhao Gong arrived to replace Xian Gong and pressed forward the work with greater vigor. At that time, the Vice-Administrator Heo Jun, who had once served at the National Academy and had thoroughly studied and investigated these ceremonies, observed that the ritual texts they had obtained were incomplete. He therefore reported this to Zhao Gong, who in turn submitted a new request to the state. They finally obtained the complete text from Ningguo and proceeded with publication. Furthermore, they appended the Ritual Procedures of the Yuan Dynasty's Zhiyuan period. Thus the sequence and order of ceremonies came close to approximating those reforms which Master Zhu had desired. Consequently, the National Confucian Academy was directed to follow and implement these procedures. This was then attached to the Ningguo publication, so that the sacrificial ritual texts, radiant and complete in all respects, formed a comprehensive work worthy of transmission to future generations.

    These gentlemen devoted themselves wholeheartedly to this task, driven by their sincere desire to perform the rituals with utmost reverence in honoring the ancient sages. Their contributions to the temple and academy, and their benefit to moral cultivation and social transformation, are indeed worthy of praise.
  footnotes:
    - Zhu Wenggong (朱文公) is Zhu Xi (1130-1200), the great Neo-Confucian philosopher, also known as Zhuzi. He was deeply concerned with restoring proper ritual practices.
    - The Kaiyuan Rituals (開元禮) were compiled during the Tang Dynasty (713 CE) and represented an authoritative codification of ritual procedures.
    - Jianwen xingyun refers to 1400 CE, during the reign of the Jianwen Emperor in Ming Dynasty China.
    - 釋奠 (Sacrificial Offerings) was a Confucian ceremony performed to honor Confucius and other sage-teachers, typically involving the presentation of symbolic offerings.
